# PROJECT REPORT 🛰️

Exoplanet Signal Intelligence System (NASA Kepler Data)

# 1. Project Report (My Explanation)🧠

I built an AI-based system to analyze NASA Kepler exoplanet data and discover hidden patterns in space signals.

The goal of my project was to understand how machine learning can help in identifying exoplanets by analyzing large, noisy astrophysical datasets.

I worked with NASA Kepler TCE data containing 34,032 samples and 113 features. The dataset includes orbital properties like period, transit depth, signal strength, and detection parameters.

Since the data was highly complex and unlabeled, I used unsupervised learning techniques to explore it.

I applied:

KMeans clustering to group similar exoplanet signals
DBSCAN to detect natural clusters and noise
Isolation Forest to find anomalies
PCA to visualize the hidden structure in 2D

I also built a simulation-style dashboard that behaves like a NASA mission control system, showing live telemetry, anomaly radar, and orbital signal fields.

My main insight was that exoplanet signals are not random — they form structured clusters, and a small portion behaves as rare anomalies.

# 2. What I Learned From This Project 🧠

While working on this project, I learned:

How real-world datasets are messy and unstructured

How important preprocessing is before ML

How clustering can reveal hidden structure without labels

How anomaly detection helps identify rare events

How PCA helps in visualizing high-dimensional data

Most importantly, I learned how to think like a data scientist working with real scientific data.

